"1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","Ghent, East Flanders, Belgium":"Ghent, East Flanders, Belgium","Badby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Badby Northamptonshire England, United Kingdom":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lincoln","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from the city of Lincoln, so named from an original British name <i>Lindo-</i> ‘lake’ + Latin <i>colonia</i> ‘settlement, colony’. The place was an important administrative center during the Roman occupation of Britain and in the Middle Ages it was a center for the manufacture of cloth, including the famous ‘Lincoln green’.","African American: adoption of the surname in 1 above, in honor of Abraham Lincoln, the 16th president of the US, who abolished slavery.","History: Abraham Lincoln (1809–65), 16th president of the US, was the son of an illiterate laborer, descended from Samuel Lincoln, who had emigrated from England to MA in 1637."],"variants":[{"name":"Linkins","meanings":["English: variant of <b>Linkin</b>, which itself is a form of   Lincoln  , prevalent in Kent."]},{"name":"Lindsay","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Lindsey in Lincolnshire, England. This is first found in the form <i>Lindissi</i>, apparently a derivative of the British name of   Lincoln  . To this was later added the Old English element <i>ēg</i> ‘island’, since the place was virtually cut off by the surrounding fenland. The surname was taken to Scotland at an early date and is the name of an important and powerful Scottish family.","Irish: adopted as an equivalent ofvarious Gaelic names (see   Lindsey  )."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry Lincoln was born in 1318, in Badby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Henry Burghersh Bishop Lincoln, was 26 and his mother, Burghersh Lincoln, was 20. He married Mrs. Henry Lincoln in 1343, in Badby, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1357, in his hometown, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1318–1357":"1318–1357","1320–1348":"1320–1348","1322–1400":"1322–1400","1338–1400":"1338–1400","1347–1400":"1347–1400","1348–1400":"1348–1400","1292–1340":"1292–1340","1298–Female":"1298–Surnud","4 December 1341":"4. detsember 1340","1340":"1340","1292":"1292","1338":"1338","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1298":"1298","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","Ghent, East Flanders, Belgium":"Gent, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgia","Badby, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Badby, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badby Northamptonshire England, United Kingdom":"Badby, Northamptonshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Badby, Northamptonshire, England":"Badby, Northamptonshire, England"},"fi":{"1318–1357":"1318–1357","1320–1348":"1320–1348","1322–1400":"1322–1400","1338–1400":"1338–1400","1347–1400":"1347–1400","1348–1400":"1348–1400","1292–1340":"1292–1340","1298–Female":"1298–Kuollut","4 December 1341":"4. joulukuuta 1340","1340":"1340","1292":"1292","1338":"1338","1348":"1348","1347":"1347","1357":"1357","1400":"1400","1322":"1322","1343":"1343","1298":"1298